{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509142"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:13:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:13:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11386"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11386"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.06,0.06,0.58,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112931"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4031"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94963"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1310"},{"type":"tags","id":"1478"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12806"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43221"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112931"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of right breast pain, redness, and swelling. She is four weeks post-partum and is currently breastfeeding. The pain worsens during breastfeeding. She has been taking regular nurofen over the last two days and has continued to breastfeed from both breasts as recommended by her midwife, but she now reports reduced milk supply and flu-like symptoms. She has no previous episodes of breast pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is generalised redness, swelling, and tenderness affecting the right breast, with no focal masses palpable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cold packs and ibuprofen","Cease breastfeeding from affected breast","Express milk with breast pump only","Flucloxacillin","Firm massage of affected breast"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with lactational mastitis with ongoing systemic symptoms including fever and flu-like symptoms despite conservative care. While mild and early cases of mastitis can be managed conservatively, the presence of ongoing systemic symptoms warrants immediate antibiotic therapy in this case. \u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line antibiotic as it covers \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, the most common causative organism for lactational mastitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECold packs and ibuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be appropriate for mild and early mastitis, but are insufficient given this patient\u0027s presentation with ongoing fever and systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing breastfeeding\u003C/strong\u003E from the affected breast is incorrect as continued breast emptying is essential for recovery. Stopping breastfeeding can lead to milk stasis and potential abscess formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpress milk with breast pump only\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as the primary management. Over-pumping or attempting to \u0022empty\u0022 the breast should be avoided, as this can worsen hyperlactation and lead to further tissue oedema and inflammation. Gentle hand expression for comfort is recommended when needed. Encouraging physiological breastfeeding is vital, with mothers advised to feed on demand as per the natural rhythm of their baby.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirm massage\u003C/strong\u003E of the affected breast can potentially worsen inflammation and cause tissue damage. Women\u0027s health physiotherapists can provide guidance on lymphatic drainage massage, a gentle technique that reduces inflammation and promotes recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management is recognising when conservative measures alone are insufficient. Systemic symptoms, fever, or significant inflammation are indicators for immediate antibiotic therapy while continuing supportive measures including regular breast emptying, analgesia, and cold packs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial management of lactational mastitis includes continued breastfeeding, cold packs, and NSAIDs.","Continued breastfeeding from the affected breast in lactational mastitis is essential to prevent complications and maintain milk supply."],"references":["Mitchell KB, Johnson HM, Rodr\u00edguez JM, Eglash A, Scherzinger C, Widmer K, Berens P, Miller B; Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine. Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine Clinical Protocol# 36: the mastitis spectrum, revised 2022. Breastfeed Med. 2022 May 1;17(5):360-76. Available from: https://www.bfmed.org/assets/ABM%20Protocol%20%2336.pdf","Mastitis. In: Australian Breastfeeding Association [online]. 2021; accessed 2021 Nov 20. Available at: https://www.breastfeeding.asn.au/resources/mastitis","Lactational Mastitis. In: Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. 2019. Available at: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=lactational-mastitis\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e47","Cusak L, Brennan M. Lactational mastitis and breast abscess: Diagnosis and Management in General Practice. Aust fam physician. 2011;40(12):976-9. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/ccf54e89-7e44-409a-afa9-c14f1bb40639/Lactational-mastitis-and-breast-abscess.aspx","Spencer, Jeanne. Management of mastitis in breastfeeding women. Am fam physician. 2008:78(6): 727-731. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2008/0915/p727.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94963"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11386"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94963"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T11:51:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T11:51:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4031"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112931"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"descriptio